# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] During the opening ceremony of the 1928 Summer Olympics, athletes from each country participating in the Olympics paraded into the arena.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] As Olympic tradition dictates, most participating nations paraded in the alphabetical order of the language of the host country (here Dutch), except Greece, who enters first at the founding nation of the Olympics, and the host country (here the Netherlands) who enters last.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] During the Parade of Nations, athletes from all participating countries entered the Olympisch Stadion.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] Each team was led by a flag bearer that was one of their athletes or officials, designated either by their respective National Olympic Committee (NOC) or by the athletes themselves.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] Below is a list of parading countries and their announced flag bearer, in the same order as the parade.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] This is sortable by country name, flag bearer's name, or flag bearer's sport.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] Names are given in the form officially designated by the IOC (International Olympic Committee).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1952-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] During the Parade of Nations section of the 1952 Summer Olympics opening ceremony, athletes from each country participating in the Olympics paraded into the arena.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1952-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The Parade of Nations was organized according to the Finnish name of the country.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1952-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Greece led the parade followed by the Netherlands Antilles.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1952-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Other countries marched by following the Finnish alphabet, except the host country, Finland, which marched last.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1952-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The athletes from British Guiana and the People's Republic of China were absent from the Parade of Nations, meaning only 67 nations participated in the parade.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals at these Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to be staged in the Southern Hemisphere and Oceania, as well as the first to be held outside Europe and North America.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne is the most southerly city ever to host the Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Australia hosted the Games for a second time in 2000 in Sydney, New South Wales, and will host them again in 2032 in Brisbane, Queensland.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympic equestrian events could not be held in Melbourne due to Australia's strict quarantine regulations, so they were held in Stockholm five months earlier.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] This was the second time the Olympics were not held entirely in one country, the first being the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium, with some events taking place in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Despite uncertainties and various complications encountered during the preparations, the 1956 Games went ahead in Melbourne as planned and turned out to be a success.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Started during the 1956 Games was the "Parade of Athletes" at the closing ceremonies.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Nine teams boycotted the Games for various reasons.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Four teams (Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon) boycotted in response to the Suez Crisis, in which Egypt was invaded by Israel, France and the United Kingdom.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Four teams (the Netherlands, Spain, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) boycotted in response to the Soviet invasion of Hungary, and the People's Republic of China's boycott was in response to a dispute with the Republic of China over the right to represent China.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] One of the most notable events of the games was a controversial water polo match between the Soviet Union and the defending champions, Hungary.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union had recently suppressed an anti-authoritarian revolution in Hungary and violence broke out between the teams during the match, resulting in numerous injuries.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] When Hungary's Ervin Zádor suffered bleeding after being punched by the Soviet Union's Valentin Prokopov, spectators attempted to join the violence, but they were blocked by police.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The match was cancelled, with Hungary being declared the winner because they were in the lead 4–0.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne was selected as the host city over bids from Buenos Aires, Mexico City, Montreal, Los Angeles, Detroit, Chicago, Minneapolis, Philadelphia, and San Francisco at the 43rd IOC Session in Rome, Italy on 28 April 1949.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Mexico City, Montreal and Los Angeles would eventually be selected to host the 1968, 1976 and 1984 Summer Olympics respectively.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Many members of the IOC were skeptical about Melbourne as an appropriate site.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Its location in the Southern Hemisphere was a major concern since the reversal of seasons would mean the Games must be held during the northern winter.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The November–December schedule was thought likely to inconvenience athletes from the Northern Hemisphere, who were accustomed to resting during their winter.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Notwithstanding these concerns, the field of candidates eventually narrowed to two Southern Hemisphere cities, these being Melbourne and Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne was selected, in 1949, to host the 1956 Olympics by a one-vote margin.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The first sign of trouble was the revelation that Australian equine quarantine would prevent the country from hosting the equestrian events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Stockholm was selected as the alternative site, so equestrian competition began on 10 June, five and a half months before the rest of the Olympic Games were to open.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The above problems of the Melbourne Games were compounded by bickering over financing among Australian politicians.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Eventually, in March 1953, the State Government accepted a £2 million loan from the Commonwealth Government to build the Olympic Village, which would accommodate up to 6,000 people, in Heidelberg West.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] After the Olympics, the houses in the village were handed back to the Housing Commission for general public housing.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] At one point, IOC President Avery Brundage suggested that Rome, which was to host the 1960 Games, was so far ahead of Melbourne in preparations that it might be ready as a replacement site in 1956.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Constructing of the sporting venues was given priority over the athlete's village.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The village was designed as a whole new suburb with semi-detached houses and flats, the first village that both sexes could cohabitate the same buildings instead of gender designated sections.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] As late as April 1955, Brundage, who was presiding over the Olympics for the first time, was still doubtful about Melbourne and was not satisfied by an inspection trip to the city.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Construction was well under way by then, thanks to a $4.5 million federal loan to Victoria, but it was behind schedule.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] He still held out the possibility that Rome might have to step in.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] By the beginning of 1956, though, it was obvious that Melbourne would be ready for the Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon announced that they would not participate in the Olympics in response to the Suez Crisis when Egypt was invaded by Israel, the United Kingdom, and France.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The Netherlands, Spain, Switzerland and Liechtenstein boycotted the event in protest of the Soviet Union's crushing of the Hungarian Revolution.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The People's Republic of China chose to boycott the event because Taiwan had been allowed to compete.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Athletes from both East and West Germany competed together as a combined team (a display of unity that was repeated in 1960 and 1964, but was then discontinued).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Although the number of countries participating (67) was almost the same as in 1952 (69), the number of athletes competing dropped sharply, from 4,925 to 3,342.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Once underway, the Games progressed smoothly, and came to be known as the "Friendly Games".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Betty Cuthbert, an 18-year-old from Sydney, won the 100 and 200 metre sprint races and ran an exceptional final leg in the 4 x 100 metre relay to overcome Great Britain's lead and claim her third gold medal, becoming known as the "Golden Girl".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The veteran Shirley Strickland repeated her 1952 win in the 80 metre hurdles and was also part of the winning 4 x 100 metre relay team, bringing her career Olympic medal total to seven: three golds, a silver, and three bronze medals.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] They won all of the freestyle races, men's and women's, and collected a total of eight gold, four silver and two bronze medals.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Murray Rose became the first male swimmer to win two freestyle events (and a total three events) since Johnny Weissmuller in 1924, while Dawn Fraser won gold medals in the 100 metre freestyle and as the leadoff swimmer in the 4 x 100 metre relay team.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The men's track and field events were dominated by the United States.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] They not only won 15 of the 24 events, they swept four of them and took first and second place in five others.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Bobby Morrow led the way with gold medals in the 100 and 200 metre sprints and the 4 x 100 metre relay.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Tom Courtney barely overtook Great Britain's Derek Johnson in the 800 metre run, then collapsed from the exertion and needed medical attention.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Ireland's Ronnie Delany ran an outstanding 53.8 over the last 400 metres to win the 1,500 metre run (also Ireland's last gold medal in track events), in which favourite John Landy of Australia finished third.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] There was a major upset, marred briefly by controversy, in the 3,000 metre steeplechase.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Little-known Chris Brasher of Great Britain finished well ahead of the field, but the judges disqualified him for interfering with Norway's Ernst Larsen, and they announced Sándor Rozsnyói of Hungary as the winner.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Brasher's appeal was supported by Larsen, Rozsnyói, and fourth-place finisher Heinz Laufer of Germany.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Subsequently, the decision was reversed and Brasher became the first Briton to win a gold medal in track and field since 1936.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Soviet runner Vladimir Kuts won two golds by winning both the 5,000-metre and 10,000-metre events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Only two world records were set in track and field.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Mildred McDaniel, the first American woman to win gold in the sport, set a high jump record of 1.76 metres (5.8 ft), and Egil Danielsen of Norway overcame blustery conditions with a remarkable javelin throw of 85.71 metres (281.2 ft).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Throughout the Olympics, Hungarian athletes were cheered by fans from Australia and other countries.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Many of them gathered in the boxing arena when thirty-year-old Laszlo Papp of Hungary won a record third gold medal by beating José Torres for the light-middleweight championship.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] A few days later, the crowd was with the Hungarian water polo team in its hotly contested and emotionally charged match against the Soviet Union which took place against the background of the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The game became rough and, when a Hungarian was forced to leave the pool with a bleeding wound above his eye, a riot almost broke out.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The police restored order and the game was called early, with Hungary leading 4–0, and the Hungarians went on to win the gold medal.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] In a much publicized Olympic romance, American hammer throw champion Hal Connolly would marry Czechoslovak discus throw champion, Olga Fikotová.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] After moving to the United States, Olga wanted to continue representing Czechoslovakia, but the Czechoslovak Olympic Committee would not allow her to do so.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Thereafter, as Olga Connolly, she took part in every Olympics until 1972 competing for the U.S.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] She was the flag bearer for the U.S. team at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The India men's national field hockey team won its sixth consecutive Olympic gold.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Despite the international tensions of 1956—or perhaps because of them—a young Melburnian, John Ian Wing, came up with a new idea for the closing ceremony.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Instead of marching as separate teams, behind their national flags, the athletes mingled together as they paraded into and around the arena for a final appearance before the spectators.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] It was the start of an Olympic tradition that has been followed ever since.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympic flame was relayed to Melbourne after being lit at Olympia on 2 November 1956.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Greek runners took the flame from Olympia to Athens.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The flame was then transferred to a miner's lamp, flown by a Qantas Super Constellation aircraft, "Southern Horizon" to Darwin, Northern Territory.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] A Royal Australian Air Force English Electric Canberra jet bomber transported the flame to Cairns, Queensland, where it arrived on 9 November 1956 and the Mayor of Cairns, Alderman W.J.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Fulton, lit the first torch with the torch design was identical to the one used for the 1948 London Games (except for the engraved city name and year).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The first runner was Con Verevis, a local man of Greek parentage.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The flame was relayed down the east coast of Australia using die cast aluminium torches weighing about 3 pounds (1.8 kg).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The flame arrived in Melbourne on 22 November 1956, the day of the opening ceremony and The flame was lit at the Olympic stadium by Ron Clarke, who accidentally burned his arm in the process.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] While the Olympic flame was being carried to Sydney, an Australian veterinary student named Barry Larkin carried a fake Olympic Flame and fooled the mayor of Sydney.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The Melbourne Olympic Arts Festival was an arts festival held in conjunction with the Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympics were first televised during the 1936 games to a domestic audience in Berlin.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The 1956 Winter Olympics in Cortina d'Ampezzo were broadcast internationally with the organising committee giving the television rights gratis.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] While there was much interest in the games overseas, no international television or newsreel rights were awarded, as the Melbourne organising committee requested licensing payments for the broadcasting rights.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] However, domestic rights to the games were hastily agreed by the then three Melbourne stations, GTV9, HSV7 and ABV2, only a week before the opening ceremony.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The three Sydney stations, TCN9, ATN7 and ABN2, syndicated the Melbourne coverage.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Television in Australia was new, having its beginnings in September 1956.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] For many Australians, their first glimpse of television were Olympic broadcasts.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Around five thousand television sets were in Australia by the time of the Games, so the domestic audience largely watched the games at community halls and at Ampol petrol stations.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] The 1956 Summer Olympics featured 17 different sports encompassing 23 disciplines, and medals were awarded in 151 events (145 events in Melbourne and 6 equestrian events in Stockholm).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] A total of 67 nations competed in the 1956 Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Eight countries made their Olympic debuts: Cambodia (only competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm), Ethiopia, Fiji, Kenya, Liberia, Malaya, North Borneo (modern-day Sabah of Malaysia), and Uganda.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Athletes from East Germany and West Germany competed together as the United Team of Germany, an arrangement that would last until 1968.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] For the first time, the team of Republic of China effectively represented only Taiwan.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Five nations competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm, but did not attend the Games in Melbourne.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Cambodia, Egypt and Lebanon did not compete in Melbourne due to a boycott regarding the Suez Crisis, whilst the Netherlands, Spain and Switzerland all boycotted the Melbourne Olympics in protest at the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Nations that returned to the games in this edition included Afghanistan and Colombia.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Helsinki 1952 but was absent in Melbourne 1956 included the People's Republic of China, Liechtenstein, Netherlands Antilles, and Saar.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Puerto Rico is an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] Bahamas, Bermuda, Fiji, Gold Coast (modern-day Ghana), Hong Kong, Jamaica, Kenya, Nigeria, Malaya, North Borneo, Singapore, Trinidad and Tobago, Uganda and British Guyana was all part of the British Empire.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1956-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1956 Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1964-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] During the Parade of Nations portion of the 1964 Summer Olympics opening ceremony, athletes from each country participating in the Olympics paraded in the arena, preceded by their flag.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1964-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The flag was borne by a sportsperson from that country chosen either by the National Olympic Committee or by the athletes themselves to represent their country.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1964-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Although the Games were held in Japan, English was used to organize the Parade of Nations instead of Japanese.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1964-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Had the parade followed the Japanese characters, Greece would have been followed by Iceland, and Rhodesia would have been the penultimate country before Japan.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1964-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The Japanese language order would not be introduced until 2020 when the country hosted the games for the fourth time.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] During the Parade of Nations section of the 1972 Summer Olympics opening ceremony, athletes from each country participating in the Olympics paraded in the arena, preceded by their flag.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] As the nation of the first modern Olympic Games, Greece entered the stadium first; whereas, the host nation West Germany marched last, according with tradition and IOC guidelines.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Announcers in the stadium read off the names of the marching nations in the host country's language, German, by actor and television personality Joachim Fuchsberger and music during the parade of nations is composed by Kurt Edelhagen.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Whilst most countries entered under their short names, a few entered under acronym or alternative names, mostly due to political and naming disputes.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] 121 nations entered the stadium with a combined total of 7,134 athletes.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Eleven nations made their Olympic debut, namely Albania, Dahomey (now Benin), Gabon, North Korea, Lesotho, Malawi, Saudi Arabia, Somalia, Swaziland, Togo, Upper Volta (now Burkina Faso).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Rhodesia's invitation to take part in the 1972 Summer Games was withdrawn by the International Olympic Committee four days before the opening ceremony, in response to African countries' (such as Ethiopia and Kenya) protests against the Rhodesian government.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] (Rhodesia did, however, compete in the 1972 Summer Paralympics, held a little earlier in Heidelberg.) Rhodesian athletes would have been marched between Republic of China and Romania.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The following is a list of each country's announced flag bearer.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The list is sorted by the order in which each nation appears in the parade of nations.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The names are given in their official designations by the IOC.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] This table is sortable by country name (in German), the flag bearer's name, and the flag bearer's sport.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] During the parade of nations section of the 1976 Summer Olympics opening ceremony, athletes from each country participating in the Olympics paraded in the arena, preceded by their flag.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The flag was borne by a sportsperson from their respective country chosen either by the National Olympic Committee or by the athletes themselves to represent their country.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] As the nation of the first modern Olympic Games, Greece entered the stadium first; whereas, the host nation Canada marched last, in accordance with the tradition and IOC guidelines.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] As each delegation entered accompanied by the music to be composed by Vic Vogel, the national name was announced in French and English (the official languages of the Olympics).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Whilst most countries entered under their short names, a few entered under acronyms or alternative names, mostly due to political and naming disputes.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] West Germany (Federal Republic of Germany) entered as **A**llemagne (*République Federal de Allemagne*), East Germany (German Democratic Republic) as **R**épublique Démocratique Allemande, North Korea (Democratic People's Republic of Korea) as **R**.P.D.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Corée (*République Populaire Démocratique de Corée*), and Soviet Union (Union of Soviet Socialist Republics) as **U**.R.S.S.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] (*Union des Républiques Socialistes Soviétiques*).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Ninety-two nations entered the stadium with a combined total of 6,084 athletes.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Four of them made their Olympic debut, namely Andorra (which had its overall Olympic debut a few months before in Innsbruck), Antigua and Barbuda (as *Antigua*), Cayman Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Because of the 1976 Summer Olympics boycott, several African countries which marched at the parade eventually withdrew from the Games, including Cameroon, Morocco, and Tunisia.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Senegal and Ivory Coast were the only African countries that competed throughout the duration of the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Elsewhere, Burma, Iraq and Guyana also opted to join the Congolese-led boycott.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Other countries, such as El Salvador and Zaire, did not participate in Montreal for purely economic reasons.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] This table is sortable by country name (in French), the flag bearer's name, and the flag bearer's sport.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] During the parade of nations portion of the 1980 Summer Olympics opening ceremony, athletes from each country participating in the Olympics paraded in the arena, preceded by their flag.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] As the nation of the first modern Olympic Games, Greece entered the stadium first; whereas, the host nation Soviet Union marched last, in accordance with the tradition and IOC guidelines.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] As each delegation entered accompanied by the Soviet march music, the national name was announced in Russian.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Eighty nations entered the stadium with a combined total of 5,179 athletes, the smallest since 1956.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Seven of them made their Olympic debut, namely Angola, Botswana, Cyprus, Jordan, Laos, Mozambique and Seychelles.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] In partial support of the United States-led boycott, sixteen countries marched into the Olympic stadium under the Olympic flag.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Seven of them, however, did not attend the opening ceremonies, their flags were instead carried by Moscow Olympic Committee volunteers.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Two other countries (Great Britain and Ireland) paraded into the Stadium only with their officials, while four of them participated under the Olympic flag with their athletes.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] New Zealand, Portugal, and Spain, on the other hand, participated in the Games under their NOC flags.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Due to the boycott, this marked the United States' first (and only) absence from the Olympics for the first time in the 84-year history.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] United States (Соединённые Штаты Америки *Soyedinyonnyye Shtaty Ameriki*, "United States of America") would have marched between Syria and Tanzania, Somalia joined the US-led boycott.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] This table is sortable by country name (in Russian), the flag bearer's name, and the flag bearer's sport.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1980-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Liberia withdrew after marching in the opening ceremony and joined the United States-led boycott.
